              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=postmodernism">postmodernism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=read-2019">read-2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2869048341" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1085121009980073669">Wahoo! In my favourites, man, I&apos;ve been having some luck this month with five star reads, and a second favourite following the beauty of John Williams&apos; &apos;Stoner&apos;. <br/><br/>This book is awesome. I&apos;ve made an equation:<br/><br/>Franz Kafka&apos;s &apos;The Trial&apos; + Monty Python = The Third Policeman<br/><br/>But it&apos;s not just that. It&apos;s reminiscent of Murakami&apos;s wild novels like &apos;Hard Boiled Wonderland and the End of the World&apos;, and it&apos;s like Father Ted, too. <br/><br/>There&apos;s a lot of madness in this book. Police stations inside the walls of oth</span>
  <span id="freeText1085121009980073669" style="display:none">Wahoo! In my favourites, man, I've been having some luck this month with five star reads, and a second favourite following the beauty of John Williams' 'Stoner'. <br /><br />This book is awesome. I've made an equation:<br /><br />Franz Kafka's 'The Trial' + Monty Python = The Third Policeman<br /><br />But it's not just that. It's reminiscent of Murakami's wild novels like 'Hard Boiled Wonderland and the End of the World', and it's like Father Ted, too. <br /><br />There's a lot of madness in this book. Police stations inside the walls of other buildings. Wind with colour. One-legged men. Turning light into sound. Bicycles becoming people and people becoming bicycles. Rooms where you don't age. All sickness come from teeth. Lining up mirrors and seeing younger versions of yourself. Death and life. And omnium, which is the very matter or well, anything, and with it you can have, well, anything.<br /><br />'Is it about a bicycle?'<br /><br />There's an awful lot of talk about bicycles. This book is fun as hell, and funny as hell too. Here's some wacky quotes to cheer up your day.<br /><br />'I knew also my soul was friendly,was my senior in years and was solely concerned for my own welfare. For convenience I called him Joe.'<br /><br />Naming your soul! <br /><br />These are five rules. They are like Asimov's rules of robotics, but not. <br /><br />'Always ask any questions that are to be asked and never answer any. Turn everything you hear to your own advantage. Always carry a repair outfit. Take left turns as much as possible. Never apply your front brake first.'<br /><br />And conversations are bonkers, random and addictive. <br /><br />'Then maybe you are no dentist at all,' he said, 'but only a man after a dog licence or papers for a bull?'<br />'I did not say I was a dentist,' I said sharply, 'and I did not say anything about a bull.'<br /><br />(For some reason the Sergeant got it in his head that our narrator was a dentist.)<br /><br />In reality, 'It seemed impossible to make the Sergeant take cognisance anything in the world except bicycles..'<br /><br />I can't say anything else. I don't know how to. Just read the book. People generally consider 'At Swim-Two-Birds' better but I didn't care for that at all, and I adore this. I already look forward to rereading it in the future. I'll end on something self-critical about myself. <br /><br />At University the two people I lived with, and my mother, and other friends, and my brother, often note how much I lean. I get it from my dad. I splay a hand and plant it on a wall and lean on it. I stick my elbow on some flat surface and lean. I just lean on anything and everything whenever I have the chance. I'm a leaner. So,<br /><br />'When a man lets things go so far that he is half or more than half a bicycle, you will not see so much because he spends a lot of his time leaning with one elbow on walls or standing propped by one foot at kerbstones.'<br /><br />With this in mind, I can confirm: I am over one half bicycle.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1085121009980073669" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


